	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>ESA*: Agricultural trade policy debates and developments</h1>

						<div class="pdf-file">
				<a href="/en/layout/set/print/content/download/12153/496950/file/f26b934c9f9842a4f23bbdcf8895e6c8.pdf">Download <img src="/extension/agritrade/design/agritrade/images/pdf.gif" alt="" /></a>
			</div>
			
			<h4>
									</h4>

						<h2>Executive brief: Update, July 2011</h2>
					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p><b>* </b>This executive brief deals with agricultural trade policy debates and developments involving the countries in Eastern and Southern Africa (ESA) which are part of the ESA-European Union Economic Partnership Agreement configuration, undertaking trade negotiations with the EU.</p><p><b>About this update</b></p><p>This brief was updated in July 2011. The original executive brief was published in October 2008 and is available on request from agritrade-mail@cta.int</p><p>Other publications in this series and additional resources on ACP—EU agriculture and fisheries trade issues can be found online at http://agritrade.cta.int/</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<a name="eztoc496940_1" id="eztoc496940_1"></a><h2><b>1. Introduction and overview </b></h2><p><b>&nbsp;</b></p><p><b>1.1 Agricultural production</b></p><p>The importance of agriculture and agro-processing varies greatly across Eastern and Southern Africa (ESA), ranging from 2% of GDP in Seychelles to 51% in Ethiopia, and accounting for between 10% (Mauritius) and 90% (Burundi and Rwanda) of employment (averaging 70% across the region). From a food security perspective, in Mauritius only 5% of the population is undernourished while in Burundi and Eritrea undernourishment affects 62% and 64% of the population respectively (and ranges elsewhere from 22% to 43%). Overall, production of the main food crops in the region is insufficient to meet consumer needs, although some countries generate periodic surpluses (e.g. Malawi). Many countries in the ESA region are vulnerable to drought.</p><p>Agriculture is dominated by small-scale producers, but large-scale commercial farms play a significant role in countries such as Malawi, Kenya and Tanzania. Livestock production is spread across the ESA group, but dominates in the north, while maize production dominates in the southern countries, and rice in Madagascar. Apart from Madagascar, island states have limited agricultural opportunities. Bananas and plantains represent important food security crops in many of the countries, and commercialisation of production is a growing priority.</p><p>2010 was a very good year for coarse grain production in ESA countries, and record harvests of coarse grains were recorded in some countries following extensive input supply programmes (e.g. in Malawi). The 2011 season has been affected by drought, leading in some instances to export bans (Tanzania) and appeals for the waiving of import taxes in maize (Kenya). Resorting to these unilateral trade policy tools, in the face of drought and threats of famine, potentially poses problems for regional trade integration in the food and agricultural sector (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/../../../../Agriculture/Commodities/Cereals/Maize-trade-policy-decisions-highlight-need-for-closer-regional-policy-harmonisation" target="_self">Maize trade policy decisions highlight need for closer regional policy h...</a>’, July 2011).</p><p>The relative importance that should be attached to agricultural production and the manufacturing of value-added food products is potentially an important area of contention within the ESA configuration. For example, Mauritius imports around 70% of its food and agricultural input requirements, and its policy is oriented towards the production of value-added food products. This leaves Mauritius favouring export subsidy programmes in certain OECD countries for certain agricultural raw materials, and this therefore influences Mauritian perspectives on rules of origin issues.</p><p><b>1.2 Agricultural trade</b></p><p>In terms of trade, the ESA region is poorly integrated. In 2009 only 2.6% of total trade occurred between ESA member states. Some 5.9% of agricultural trade however took place between ESA member states. There is considerable variation in the extent of intra-ESA trade between products. Sectors with higher rates of intra-ESA agricultural trade include: beverages and spirits (22%); coffee, tea and spices (15%); and sugar and milled cereal products (12%).</p><p>There is also considerable variation between sub-regions. Within the East African Community (EAC), some 7% of agricultural trade occurs between EAC member states, with the rate much higher in meat and edible offal (32%); live animals (30%); dairy products (30%); beverages and spirits (26%); and sugar and sugar confectionery (10%).</p><p>Within the ESA grouping Kenya is both the main agricultural exporter (26% of the total) and the main agricultural importer (18.3% of the total). As an important transportation hub, Kenya is also at the heart of intra-regional trade. Within the smaller EAC grouping, Kenya’s economic dominance has traditionally been a matter of political concern.</p><p>The ESA region’s main agricultural exports include tea, coffee and spices (23.3%); tobacco (14%); horticultural products (17.1%); cotton (4.4%); and increasingly sugar (6.1%). In the past 15 years, export-oriented horticultural production has developed significantly, while in the past 10 years substantial new investments have been made in the sugar sector and associated value-added processing activities.</p><p>The main agricultural product imports are: cereals (31%); animal and vegetable fats and oils (16%); and sugar products (7%). In the northern zone of the ESA region, dairy products and processed tomatoes are also significant imports.</p><p>Considerable scope exists for the development of intra-regional trade in basic cereals. This is a sensitive issue, with a wide variety of trade policy tools being deployed on food security grounds (from export bans to import restrictions linked to quality standards). Addressing food availability concerns in an era of rising prices and increased vulnerability to climate-related events poses a significant regional policy challenge. Yet facilitating intra-regional trade, so that food can move freely from food-surplus to food-deficit areas, can be seen as a critical response to these challenges.</p><p>In the sugar sector, with the decline in EU preferential prices, regional markets are now looking increasingly attractive to ESA producers, with increased regional trade evident (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/../../../../Agriculture/Commodities/Sugar/Regional-sugar-trade-and-production-in-Eastern-and-Southern-Africa-growing" target="_self">Regional sugar trade and production in Eastern and Southern Africa growing</a>’, July 2011). Considerable investment is taking place in the expansion of sugar production in ESA member states (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/../../../../en/Agriculture/Commodities/Sugar/Investments-under-way-to-expand-ESA-sugar-production" target="_self">Investments under way to expand ESA sugar production</a>’, May 2011). Certain ESA sub-regions are net sugar importers, with a policy orientation towards self-sufficiency (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/../../../../en/Agriculture/Commodities/Sugar/ESA-Investments-under-way-to-prepare-for-regional-free-trade-in-sugar" target="_self">ESA: Investments under way to prepare for regional free trade in sugar</a>’, March 2011), yet the region as whole is a net sugar exporter. This could potentially generate trade conflicts (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/../../../../Agriculture/Topics/ACP-regional-trade/ESA-Clock-ticking-for-Kenya-s-sugar-industry-under-regional-market-opening" target="_self">ESA: Clock ticking for Kenya’s sugar industry under regional market opening</a>’, February 2011).</p><p>Beyond issues of intra-regional trade, coffee represents a potential area for regional cooperation on marketing of single-origin coffees, with considerable potential for the development of greater value-added processing and packaging in the coffee sector (modelled on the ‘authentic Caribbean rum’ programme).</p><p>Horticulture also represents an area for intensified cooperation in reducing the costs of SPS and food safety compliance, and developing intra-regional trade in horticultural products.</p><p>In the cotton sector, meanwhile, initiatives are under way to strengthen the functioning of the supply chain to provide greater income stability to primary producers. Considerable scope exists for regional cooperation on policies to strengthen the functioning of supply chains, potentially providing low-cost, sustainable solutions to problems related to the commercial viability of smallholder farming systems.</p><p>The EU is the main agricultural trade partner of the ESA region, providing a market for 42.8% of the ESA group’s food and agricultural exports and 15.7% of the region’s food and agricultural imports. South Africa is also an important supplier, particularly to countries in the southern part of the ESA region. These points are important in the evolving discussions on the conclusion of a tripartite free-trade area (FTA) agreement, including the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA), the Southern African Development Community (SADC) and the EAC (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/../../../../Agriculture/Topics/ACP-FTAs/Road-map-for-trilateral-FTA-agreed" target="_self">Road map for Trilateral FTA agreed</a>’, August 2011).</p><p>China is growing in importance as an export market. A critical issue facing the region is whether the emergence of China as a competitor for the region’s food and agricultural exports can be exploited to attract investment in value-added processing which will move regional production up the value chain (e.g. expanding coffee roasting and packaging facilities, and local tea blending and packaging) (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/../Africa%20urged%20to%20diversify%20and%20structurally%20transform" target="_self">Africa urged to diversify and structurally transform</a>’, July 2011). In this context, India’s renewed interest in intensifying economic collaboration with Eastern and Southern African economies could also offer scope for attracting investment in moving up the value chain (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/../../../../en/Agriculture/Topics/ACP-regional-trade/India-looks-for-increased-trade-and-economic-cooperation-with-Africa" target="_self">India looks for increased trade and economic cooperation with Africa</a>’, July 2011).</p><p><b>Table 1: ESA countries’ main sources of agricultural imports and agricultural export markets (2008–2009, in US$ millions)</b></p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
<tr>
