<p>Source: compiled by the author</p><p>The fact that governments have multiple, overlapping membership of these regional trade bodies means that coordinating agricultural trade policy at a regional level is made highly complicated. Efforts are underway to harmonise these regional trade arrangements through the establishment of a ‘grand’ tripartite FTA (T-FTA).</p><p>The situation is further complicated by the fact that four countries are members of COMESA but not part of the ESA grouping. These are:</p>
<ul>

<li>The Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC). The DRC is a part of the Central Africa negotiating configuration for EU Economic Partnership Agreements (EPAs).</li>

<li>Swaziland, which is a member of SACU and also the SADC EPA configuration.</li>

<li>Egypt and Libya, which are non-ACP states that together account for over half of the GDP of COMESA.</li>

</ul>
<p>However the most basic complicating factor arises from the differing national policies on the use of agricultural and agricultural trade policy tools.<b> </b></p><p><b>&nbsp;</b></p><a name="eztoc496940_2" id="eztoc496940_2"></a><h2><b>2. Regional agricultural trade policy developments</b></h2><p><b>&nbsp;</b></p><p><b>2.1 Agriculture in the national context</b></p><p>Agriculture makes a far greater contribution to employment creation than it does to GDP and merchandise exports. Indeed, livelihood concerns can come to dominate policy formulation. In some ESA economies, agro-food value-added processing activities make a larger contribution to GDP than agricultural activities <i>per se</i>. This gives rise to very different agricultural trade policy perspectives compared to countries where agriculture is the mainstay of livelihoods for the majority of the population.</p><p><b>Table 3: Role of agriculture in ESA national economies</b></p><table class="renderedtable" border="0" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" width="582">
