<p>Source: FAO, ‘L’état de l’insécurité alimentaire mondiale dans le monde’, 2010. Available from:</p><p>
<a href="http://www.fao.org/docrep/013/i1683f/i1683f.pdf" target="_self">http://www.fao.org/docrep/013/i1683f/i1683f.pdf</a></p><p>Notes: 1. World Bank, 2009; 2. FAO, 2002, 2003 and 2004; 3. FAO, 2005–07.</p><p>Despite the efforts under way to bring about regional coordination, agriculture and agricultural trade policy remain a national responsibility. Governments have different perspectives on what constitute appropriate policy tools for the promotion of agricultural development and the relative importance to be accorded to the use of specific tools. Some governments favour the use of financial support measures, such as input subsidy programmes, as a means of promoting agricultural development in key sectors. Other governments favour the more extensive use of trade policy tools to promote the development of specific sectors. Most governments deploy a combination of financial support instruments (mainly input supply programmes) and trade policy tools.</p><p>Building consensus on what agricultural trade policy tools can be used, and how they can be used, is likely to prove a difficult task. This is made more difficult by the conflation of the use of trade policy tools with discussions on the elimination of other non-tariff barriers to trade (NTBs) (such as cumbersome customs administration procedures; divergent technical standards; illegal transport control points; logistical infrastructure constraints and the serious problems of transportation constraints). It is important to make a distinction between these non-tariff obstacles to trade and the transparent and accountable use of trade policy tools within an agreed regional policy framework.</p><p><b>Table 4: Policy related non-tariff barriers to agricultural trade among ESA countries</b></p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
<tr>
